SIMPLE: manufacture
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manufacture
<hw>Man`u*fac"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>manus</ets> the hand + <ets>factura</ets> a making, fr.
<ets>facere</ets> to make: cf. F. <ets>manufacture</ets>. See
<er>Manual</er>, and <er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
operation of making wares or any products by hand, by machinery, or by
other agency.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything made from raw materials by the hand, by
machinery, or by art, as cloths, iron utensils, shoes, machinery,
saddlery, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Manufacture
<hw>Man`u*fac"ture</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Manufactured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Manufacturing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>manufacturer</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make (wares or other
products) by hand, by machinery, or by other agency; <as>as, to
<ex>manufacture</ex> cloth, nails, glass, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To work, as raw or partly wrought materials, into
suitable forms for use; <as>as, to <ex>manufacture</ex> wool, cotton,
silk, or iron</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Manufacture
<hw>Man`u*fac"ture</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be employed in
manufacturing something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manufactured</ent>⟦br⟧
